A \\blue{closed} or \\blue{periodic} billiard trajectory in a triangle.
\\begin{center}\n{\\bf \\large \\blue{A phenomenon discovered by Schwartz:}}\n\\end{center}
\\begin{center}\n{\\bf \\large \\blue{Parallels for Isosceles triangles}}\n\\end{center}
\\begin{center}\n{\\bf \\large \\blue{Todays Goal:}}\n\\end{center}
{\\bf \\color{Purple} Open Question:} Does every polygon admit a periodic billiard\\\\\ntrajectory?
{\\bf \\color{Purple} Theorem (Schwartz):} Every triangle with largest\nangle less than $100^\\circ$ has a periodic billiard trajectory.
{\\bf \\color{Purple} Theorem (Schwartz):} The function $L$ is finite at each triangle with largest angle less than $100^\\circ$.
Let $P$ be a polygon in the plane. We define $L(P)$\nto be the length of the shortest periodic billiard trajectory\nin $P$ or $\\infty$ if none exists.
{\\bf \\color{Purple} Theorem (Schwartz):} The function $L$ is not locally finite at the $(30,60,90)$ triangle.

{\bf \color{Purple} Conjecture (H-Schwartz):} The function $L$ is not 
locally finite 
at the triangle with angles 
\vspace{-1em}
$$\left(\frac{\pi}{2^{k}},\frac{\pi}{2^{k}},\frac{\pi(2^{k-1}-1)}{2^{k-1}}\right)$$
\vspace{-2em}

for any integer $k \geq 3$.
I\'ll give some ideas that I expect will lead to a proof of this\\\\ conjecture.
{\\large \\bf \\blue{Idea 1:}} Consider real analytic paths of polygons.

{\bf \color{Purple} Theorem (Criterion for non-local boundedness):}\\
Let $t \mapsto P_t$ be real analytic and defined on $[0,a)$ for some $a>0$.
If $L$ is locally bounded at $P_0$, then
there is an $\epsilon>0$ and a single orbit type $\sO$ so that $P_t$ lies in
the orbit tile of $\sO$ for $0<t< \epsilon$.

{\\bf \\color{Purple} A related classification problem:}\\\\\nGiven $t \\mapsto P_t$ real analytic, find all $\\sO$ so that there is an $\\epsilon>0$\nso that $P_t$ lies in the orbit tile when $0<t<\\epsilon$.
\\begin{center}\n{\\bf \\large \\blue{The translation surface associated to a polygon:}}\n\\end{center}
Given a polygon $P$, let $DP$ denote the double of $P$ across\nits boundary.
{\\bf \\color{Purple} Fact:} The periodic billiard trajectories on $P$ are precisely the images of closed geodesics on the minimal translation surface cover of $P$.

So, for the $(45,45,90)$ triangle, the periodic billiard trajectories can be explicitly enumerated. \nBy observations of Veech, this holds more generally for the $(30,60,90)$ triangle\nand the $(\\frac{\\pi}{2n}\\frac{\\pi}{2n}, \\ast)$ \\\\ triangles.
\\begin{center}\n{\\bf \\large \\blue{Translation surfaces associated to a real analytic path of polygons:}}\n\\end{center}

Let $t\mapsto P_t$ be a real analytic path of polygons defined on $[0,a)$ for some $a>0$. 
Then, for each $t$, we get a rotational holonomy homomorphism:
\vspace{-1.5em}

$$\hol_t: \pi_1(DP_t^\ast) \to \R / 2 \pi \Z.$$
\vspace{-2em}

The associated \blue{analytic path of translation surfaces} is the family of covers
of $DP_t^\ast$ associated to $\bigcap_t \ker(\hol_t)$.
Again, sometimes $S_0$ admits special symmetries allowing for the classification of closed geodesics.

{\bf \color{Purple} Theorem:} Let $P_t$ be a real analytic path of triangles 
with $P_0$ the $(\frac{\pi}{2^{k}},\frac{\pi}{2^{k}},\ast)$ triangle for an integer $k \geq 3$. 
If $P_t$ is not contained in a line in the space of triangles, then there are no orbit types
so that $P_t$ lies in the orbit tile for $0 \leq t < \epsilon$ for a positive $\epsilon$.
\\begin{center}\n{\\bf \\large \\blue{Streched limits of analytic paths of translation surfaces:}}\n\\end{center}
{\\bf \\color{Purple} Observations:} \n

\begin{itemize}
\item Translation surfaces arising from polygonal billiard tables are special: 
All singularities are of cone type, and the distance between singularities is bounded from below by some $\eta>0$. We call such surfaces \blue{$\eta$-forthright}.
\item There is a natural definition of an real analytic path in the space of pointed $\eta$-forthright surfaces having to do with the motion of cone singularities. This singularites move around in a real analytic way, except they may tend to $\infty$.
\item There is a naural way to identify homotopy classes within an analytic family. Closed geodesics lie in a cylinder whose circumferences and widths vary real analytically in $t$.
\item There is a $\GL(2,\R)$ action on translation surfaces, and it preserves the forthright surfaces.
\item The $\eta$-forthright surfaces form a closed set in a natural topology on the space of all pointed translation surfaces. 
This topology is described in a pair of articles on the ArXiv, {\em Immersions and translation structures on the disk} and {\em Immersions and the space of all translation structures}.
\end{itemize}

{\\bf \\color{Purple} Theorem (Using streched limits):} \\\\\nSuppose a family of cylinders in $S_t$ is assymptotically horizontal as $t \\to 0$ and\nhas width function $w(t)=ct+O(t^2)$. If the homotopy class has a limit in $S\'_0=\\lim_{t \\to 0} A_t(S_t)$,\nthen there is a cylinder in this homotopy class.
{\\bf \\color{Purple} Example:} \n
{\\bf \\color{Purple} Fact (Classification):} \\\\\nIn some cases, the \\\\\nsuccessive strecthed \\\\\nlimits of an analytic \\\\\nfamily $t \\mapsto S_t$ can be \\\\\nclassified.

{\bf \color{Purple} Fact:} Let $t \mapsto P_t$ be as above, and let $t \mapsto S_t$ be the analytic path of translation surfaces.
Let $\gamma$ be periodic billiard path in $P_0$ with orbit type $\sO$.
Then, $P_t$ lies in the orbit tile of $\sO$ (with $\sO$ of even length) for $0 \leq t<\epsilon$ for some $\epsilon>0$
if and only if $\gamma$ lifts to $S_0$.
{\\bf \\color{Purple} Theorem (H-Schwartz):} There is a neighborhood of the \nset of isosceles triangles so that every triangle in the neighborhood has a periodic billiard trajectory.

{\bf \color{Purple} Theorem (Stretched limits):} \\
Let $t \mapsto S_t$ be a real analytic path in the space of $\eta$-forthright surface defined for $t \in [0,a)$.
Define the family of matrices:
\vspace{-1em}

$$A_t=\left[\begin{array}{rr} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & \frac{1}{t} \end{array}\right].$$
\vspace{-1.5em}

Then, there is a limit $S'_0=\lim_{t \to 0} A_t(S_t)$. 
Furthermore, the path defined by $S'_0$ and $S'_t=A_t(S_t)$ for $t \in [0,a)$
is a real analytic path of $\eta$-forthright translation surfaces.
\\begin{center}\n{\\bf \\large \\blue{Some terminology}}\n\\end{center}
{\\large \\bf \\blue{Idea 1:}} We should study real analytic paths in the space of\\\\ polygons.\n

\begin{itemize}
\item A \blue{\bf marked polygon}, $P$, is a $n$-gon in the plane with
edges labeled cyclically by $\Z/n\Z$.
\item Let $\gamma$ be a periodic billiard trajectory in $P$. Its \blue{\bf orbit type}, $\sO_\gamma$, is 
the cyclic sequence of labels of edges hit by $\gamma$.
\item If $\sO$ is a cyclic sequence in $\Z/n\Z$, then its \blue{\bf orbit tile} is
the set of $n$-gons in the plane which have a periodic
billiard trajectory with orbit type $\sO$.
\end{itemize}
{\\bf \\color{Purple} Proposition:} If $K$ is a compact set of marked polygons\nand $L$ is bounded on $K$, then $K$ has a finite covering by\norbit tiles.
{\\bf Proof:} On K, the length of a periodic billiard path is\nbounded from below by a constant, c(K), times the length\nof the path\'s orbit type.
{\\bf Proof:}

{\bf \color{Purple} Corollary (Criterion for non-local boundedness):}\\
Let $t \mapsto P_t$ be real analytic and defined on $[0,a)$ for some $a>0$.
If $L$ is locally bounded at $P_0$, then
there is an $\epsilon>0$ and a single orbit type $\sO$ so that $P_t$ lies in
the orbit tile of $\sO$ for $0<t< \epsilon$.

{\bf \color{Purple} Proposition (The real analytic shape of orbit tiles):}\\
Let $\sO$ be a cyclic sequence in $\Z/n\Z$. Its orbit tile is a set of polygons 
$P$ determined in the following way:
\begin{enumerate}
\item An integer linear combination of the angles of $P$ must vanish.
\item A finite number of real analytic functions in the
vertices of $P$ must be positive.
\end{enumerate}
